---

<Layout title={pageTitle} description={pageDescription}>
  <section class="section">
    <article class="card lesson-page">
      <header class="lesson-header">
        <div class="lesson-label-row">
          <span class="badge badge-level">C1 ¬∑ Advanced Grammar</span>
          <span class="badge badge-exams">IELTS &amp; CELPIP</span>
        </div>
        <h1>‚ú® The Advanced Uses of <span class="highlight">‚ÄúWould‚Äù</span></h1>
        <p class="lesson-intro">
          <strong>Would</strong> is not just the ‚Äúconditional word.‚Äù At C1 level, it
          expresses <em>habituality, tentativeness, hypotheticality, politeness,
          volition, narrative projection, and reported stance</em>. This lesson takes a
          descriptive approach similar to Leech‚Äôs reference grammar, but stays practical
          for exam performance.
        </p>

        <div class="lesson-overview-grid">
          <div class="mini-card">
            <h3>üéØ Lesson goals</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Distinguish the main functions of <strong>would</strong>.</li>
              <li>Use <strong>would</strong> to signal advanced stance and politeness.</li>
              <li>Avoid typical C1 mistakes in IELTS &amp; CELPIP tasks.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="mini-card callout callout-info">
            <h3>Exam payoff üí°</h3>
            <p>
              Accurate use of <strong>would</strong> is strong evidence of
              high-level control of modality and discourse. Examiners love this.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </header>

      <!-- 1. WOULD FOR PAST HABIT -->
      <section class="lesson-section">
        <h2>1. üîÅ <span class="key-word">Would</span> for past habit (repeated actions)</h2>
        <p>
          Here, <strong>would</strong> marks <em>repeated, characteristic actions</em> in
          the past. It does <strong>not</strong> normally describe states.
        </p>

        <div class="example-grid">
          <div class="example-block">
            <div class="example-label good">‚úÖ Natural</div>
            <p>
              <span class="emph">When I worked in Toronto, I would take the Lakeshore
              train every morning.</span>
            </p>
            <p class="note">
              Repeated action, anchored in time by <em>when I worked in Toronto</em>.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="example-block">
            <div class="example-label bad">‚ö†Ô∏è Odd</div>
            <p>
              <span class="emph">When I was younger, I would know all my neighbours.</span>
            </p>
            <p class="note">
              <strong>Know</strong> is a state. Use
              <span class="emph-alt">used to know</span> or simple past instead.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="callout callout-neutral">
          <strong>Leech-style note üß†</strong><br />
          <strong>Would</strong> for past habit assumes a
          <em>temporal frame is already active</em>. You usually cannot open a story with
          <em>‚ÄúI would visit my grandmother every weekend‚Äù</em> without first establishing
          <em>when</em>.
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 2. TENTATIVE / SOFTENED ASSERTION -->
      <section class="lesson-section">
        <h2>2. üé≠ Tentative or softened assertion</h2>
        <p>
          In advanced discourse, <strong>would</strong> marks your stance as
          <em>cautious</em> or <em>polite</em>, not simply conditional.
        </p>

        <div class="example-strip">
          <div>
            <p class="emph">I would argue that this policy is ineffective.</p>
            <p class="note">Cautious, distance-creating. Good for IELTS Writing Task 2.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <p class="emph">I would suggest starting with Task 2.</p>
            <p class="note">Softens the recommendation.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <p class="emph">I wouldn‚Äôt say the results were impressive.</p>
            <p class="note">Polite understatement rather than direct criticism.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="callout callout-accent">
          <strong>Exam tip üéì</strong><br />
          Tentative <strong>would</strong> is especially valuable in
          <em>IELTS Speaking Part 3</em> and <em>CELPIP Speaking tasks</em>, where examiners
          listen for nuanced stance rather than absolute statements.
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 3. HYPOTHETICALITY -->
      <section class="lesson-section">
        <h2>3. üå´ Hypothetical / remote situations</h2>
        <p>
          Here, <strong>would</strong> expresses <em>remoteness from reality</em>: unreal,
          unlikely, or purely imagined situations.
        </p>

        <ul class="bullet-list">
          <li><span class="emph">I would attend the meeting if I had more time.</span></li>
          <li><span class="emph">Most people would choose convenience over quality.</span></li>
          <li><span class="emph">Without public transport, many residents would struggle.</span></li>
        </ul>

        <p class="note">
          This is not ‚Äúfuture tense.‚Äù It is a modal marking <strong>distance</strong> from
          reality (semantic remoteness).
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- 4. POLITENESS -->
      <section class="lesson-section">
        <h2>4. ü§ù Politeness and social distancing</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Would</strong> softens requests, offers, and refusals. This is
          high-level pragmatic control.
        </p>

        <div class="example-grid">
          <div class="example-block">
            <p class="emph">Would you mind clarifying that point?</p>
            <p class="note">More polite than <em>Can you clarify that?</em></p>
          </div>
          <div class="example-block">
            <p class="emph">I would appreciate more details about the survey.</p>
            <p class="note">Polite, formal tone for emails and CELPIP writing.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="example-block">
            <p class="emph">I wouldn‚Äôt be able to attend tomorrow.</p>
            <p class="note">Softened refusal.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 5. VOLITION -->
      <section class="lesson-section">
        <h2>5. üí™ Volition and ‚Äúrefusal‚Äù in the past</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Would</strong> can show <em>willingness</em> or <em>stubborn behaviour</em>
          in the past. With inanimate subjects, it often signals metaphorical ‚Äúrefusal.‚Äù
        </p>

        <ul class="bullet-list">
          <li><span class="emph">He would always help anyone who asked.</span></li>
          <li><span class="emph">She wouldn‚Äôt listen to anyone‚Äôs advice.</span></li>
          <li><span class="emph">The car wouldn‚Äôt start again.</span></li>
        </ul>

        <p class="note">
          In the last example, the car has no will, but English uses
          <em>wouldn‚Äôt</em> to personify mechanical failure.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- 6. NARRATIVE DISPLACEMENT -->
      <section class="lesson-section">
        <h2>6. üìö Narrative displacement (‚Äúfuture in the past‚Äù)</h2>
        <p>
          This use presents an event as <em>future from a past viewpoint</em>. It is common
          in narrative and reflective writing.
        </p>

        <div class="example-strip timeline">
          <div>
            <p class="emph">I didn‚Äôt know that this decision would change my life.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <p class="emph">They were unaware that the storm would intensify overnight.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <p class="emph">The experiment would later become a model for others.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="note">
          This is useful in IELTS Task 2 when you describe past decisions and their later
          impact, and in CELPIP when telling stories or experiences.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- 7. REPORTED SPEECH -->
      <section class="lesson-section">
        <h2>7. üó£ Reported speech</h2>
        <p>
          In reported speech, <strong>would</strong> often corresponds to
          <strong>will</strong> in the original statement.
        </p>

        <div class="example-grid">
          <div class="example-block">
            <div class="example-label good">Direct</div>
            <p class="emph">‚ÄúI will call you tomorrow,‚Äù she said.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="example-block">
            <div class="example-label good">Reported</div>
            <p class="emph">She said she would call me the next day.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="callout callout-neutral">
          <strong>Subtlety üß©</strong><br />
          If the situation is still true, English may keep <em>will</em>:
          <br />
          <span class="emph-alt">
            The teacher said the exam will be next Monday.
          </span>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 8. CONTRAST TABLE -->
      <section class="lesson-section">
        <h2>8. ‚öñÔ∏è Would vs. Used to vs. Past simple</h2>

        <div class="contrast-table-wrapper">
          <table class="contrast-table">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Form</th>
                <th>Typical use</th>
                <th>States?</th>
                <th>Extra nuance</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>would</strong></td>
                <td>Repeated actions in past</td>
                <td>‚ùå (normally not)</td>
                <td>Requires context; adds narrative viewpoint</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>used to</strong></td>
                <td>Past habits and states</td>
                <td>‚úÖ</td>
                <td>Neutral, common in spoken narrative</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>past simple</strong></td>
                <td>Single or repeated events</td>
                <td>‚úÖ</td>
                <td>No special extra meaning; default form</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 9. EXAM APPLICATION -->
